 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e458673a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Tutorial 3: Fitting the Top Quark Mass\n",
    "\n",
    "In this tutorial we will learn how to extract a parameter of interest like the top quark mass from an invariant mass distribution. We'll simulate a typical top mass measurement where templates are generated for different mass hypotheses.\n",
    "\n",
    "We use a technique where the mass dependence is implemented as a continuous shape systematic variation, mapping the mass variation (e.g., $\\Delta m_t$) as an unconstrained parameter in the fit."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cfc9b080",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setting up the environment"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "a18eb0ed",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import os\n",
    "import sys\n",
    "from pathlib import Path\n",
    "\n",
    "# 1. Emulate RABBIT_BASE (points to the 'rabbit' root)\n",
    "rabbit_base = str(Path(os.getcwd()).parent.absolute())\n",
    "os.environ['RABBIT_BASE'] = rabbit_base\n",
    "\n",
    "# 2. Append rabbit_base to PYTHONPATH so `import rabbit` works\n",
    "if rabbit_base not in sys.path:\n",
    "    sys.path.append(rabbit_base)\n",
    "\n",
    "# 3. Emulate sourcing setup.sh by putting rabbit/bin in PATH\n",
    "rabbit_bin = os.path.join(rabbit_base, 'bin')\n",
    "current_path = os.environ.get('PATH', '')\n",
    "if rabbit_bin not in current_path:\n",
    "    os.environ['PATH'] = f\"{current_path}:{rabbit_bin}\"\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"RABBIT_BASE:\", os.environ['RABBIT_BASE'])\n",
    "print(\"PATH:\", os.environ['PATH'])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e578c2e0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Generating the invariant mass distribution\n",
    "\n",
    "We will generate an invariant mass distribution representing the reconstructed top quark mass. \n",
    "We use pseudo-data and generate a signal peak on top of a background. The signal peak position depends on the top quark mass."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "18f99dc2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import hist\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import mplhep as hep\n",
    "from rabbit import tensorwriter\n",
    "hep.style.use(\"CMS\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create an output directory for the results\n",
    "outdir = \"results/top_mass\"\n",
    "os.makedirs(outdir, exist_ok=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define an axis for the reconstructed top mass\n",
    "mass_axis = hist.axis.Regular(40, 130, 210, name=\"m_top\", label=\"Reconstructed Mass [GeV]\")\n",
    "\n",
    "def get_hist(axis):\n",
    "    return hist.Hist(axis, storage=hist.storage.Weight())\n",
    "\n",
    "# Nominal top mass and variations\n",
    "m_top_nom = 172.5\n",
    "dm = 1.0 # 1 GeV variation\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "n_sig = 50000\n",
    "n_bkg = 20000\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate background (exponential or broad distribution)\n",
    "bkg_mass = np.random.uniform(130, 210, n_bkg)\n",
    "h_bkg = get_hist(mass_axis)\n",
    "h_bkg.fill(bkg_mass)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Function to generate signal given a top mass\n",
    "def generate_signal(m_top):\n",
    "    # simple Gaussian resolution\n",
    "    resolution = 15.0\n",
    "    mass = np.random.normal(m_top, resolution, n_sig)\n",
    "    h = get_hist(mass_axis)\n",
    "    h.fill(mass)\n",
    "    return h\n",
    "\n",
    "h_sig_nom = generate_signal(m_top_nom)\n",
    "h_sig_up = generate_signal(m_top_nom + dm)\n",
    "h_sig_dn = generate_signal(m_top_nom - dm)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Pseudodata (we will inject m_top = 173.2 GeV)\n",
    "m_top_true = 173.2\n",
    "h_sig_true = generate_signal(m_top_true)\n",
    "h_data = get_hist(mass_axis)\n",
    "h_data.view()[...] = h_sig_true.view() + h_bkg.view()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the templates\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
    "hep.histplot([h_bkg, h_sig_nom], stack=True, histtype='fill', label=['Background', 'Signal (m_t=172.5)'], ax=ax)\n",
    "hep.histplot(h_data, histtype='errorbar', color='black', label=f'Data (m_t={m_top_true})', ax=ax)\n",
    "ax.legend()\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Events\")\n",
    "plt.savefig(f\"{outdir}/templates.png\", bbox_inches=\"tight\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d7fc9d8b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Writing the tensor\n",
    "\n",
    "We encode the mass dependence as a shape variation (`mass_shift`) and declare it as an unconstrained parameter (`constrained=False`). This tells the fitter to treat the shift as a freely floating parameter instead of pulling it to a Gaussian prior."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "5fa23d13",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "writer = tensorwriter.TensorWriter()\n",
    "\n",
    "writer.add_channel(h_data.axes, \"mass_region\")\n",
    "writer.add_data(h_data, \"mass_region\")\n",
    "\n",
    "writer.add_process(h_sig_nom, \"signal\", \"mass_region\", signal=True)\n",
    "writer.add_process(h_bkg, \"background\", \"mass_region\", signal=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add standard background normalization uncertainty\n",
    "writer.add_norm_systematic(\"bkg_norm\", \"background\", \"mass_region\", 1.10) # 10% uncertainty\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add the mass variation as an UNCONSTRAINED systematic\n",
    "# Since we generated up/dn variations with +/- 1 GeV, \n",
    "# a value of +1 for this parameter means m_t = 173.5 GeV.\n",
    "writer.add_systematic(\n",
    "    [h_sig_up, h_sig_dn], \n",
    "    \"top_mass_shift\", \n",
    "    \"signal\", \n",
    "    \"mass_region\", \n",
    "    symmetrize=\"average\", \n",
    "    constrained=False,  # This is the key for a parameter measurement!\n",
    "    noi=True            # Nuisance parameter of interest\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "out_hdf5 = f\"{outdir}/top_mass_tensor.hdf5\"\n",
    "writer.write(outfolder=outdir, outfilename=\"top_mass_tensor\")\n",
    "print(f\"Tensor written to {out_hdf5}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e7c2c547",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Running the fit\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we run the maximum likelihood fit to extract the top mass. We will scan the `top_mass_shift` parameter to compute the likelihood profile and its uncertainty. By default, `rabbit_fit.py` scans parameters specified with `--scan`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "3127cd0f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Run the fit on data (-t 0) unblinded, and scan the 'top_mass_shift' parameter\n",
    "!rabbit_fit.py {outdir}/top_mass_tensor.hdf5 -t 0 -o {outdir} --scan top_mass_shift --unblind --postfix mass_fit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "89b7fa58",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Interpreting the result\n",
    "\n",
    "We can check the parameter pulls and constraints. The `top_mass_shift` is an unconstrained parameter, so its \"pull\" is actually the best fit value of the parameter."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "27027a03",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "!rabbit_print_pulls_and_constraints.py {outdir}/fitresults_mass_fit.hdf5"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a92b3a9c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We set up our templates such that +1 on `top_mass_shift` corresponds to +1 GeV in mass relative to 172.5 GeV.\n",
    "Our pseudodata was generated with $m_{top} = 173.2$ GeV. The fitted value of `top_mass_shift` should therefore be close to `0.7`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f51bb176",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Plotting the likelihood scan\n",
    "\n",
    "We can plot the likelihood profile we scanned during the fit. The scan output provides the 1D $\\Delta \\ln \\mathcal{L}$ curve."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "f5bb5415",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "!rabbit_plot_likelihood_scan.py {outdir}/fitresults_mass_fit.hdf5 --param top_mass_shift -o {outdir}\n",
    "\n",
    "from IPython.display import HTML, display\n",
    "import time\n",
    "v = time.time()\n",
    "display(HTML(\n",
    "    f'<img src=\"{outdir}/nll_scan_top_mass_shift_data_unblinded.png?v={v}\" style=\"width: 60%;\" />'\n",
    "))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "19b7a159",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The minimum of the parabola corresponds to the best fit mass shift. The width of the parabola at $2\\Delta \\ln \\mathcal{L} = 1$ gives the $1\\sigma$ uncertainty."
   ]
  }
 ],
